# DSP — When NOT to Update

Not every code change requires a DSP update. Skip DSP operations for internal-only changes that don't affect the project's structural graph.

## Do NOT Update DSP For

- **Formatting changes** — whitespace, indentation, line breaks, prettier/eslint fixes
- **Comment edits** — adding, removing, or rewriting comments and documentation strings
- **Private function body changes** — refactoring internals without changing the function's signature or purpose
- **Dependency version bumps** — updating package.json, requirements.txt, Cargo.toml versions
- **Config file tweaks** — .env, .gitignore, tsconfig.json, eslint config, CI pipeline YAML
- **Test internals** — changing test assertions, adding test cases (unless the test architecture itself changes)
- **Logging/debugging** — adding or removing console.log, print statements, debug breakpoints
- **Performance optimizations** — internal algorithm changes that don't alter the module's interface or purpose

## DO Update DSP When

- Creating or deleting source files
- Renaming or moving files
- Adding or removing module dependencies (imports)
- Changing a module's public API (exports, shared interfaces)
- Changing a module's core purpose or responsibility
- Splitting one module into multiple or merging modules
